</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing Tomato and Pepper Trays</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Choosing only by plant count:</strong> more cells do not help if peppers crowd out before spring is ready.</li>
    <li><strong>Assuming tomatoes and peppers need identical tray timing:</strong> peppers usually need more margin.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring delayed transplant windows:</strong> the tray should match real spring timing, not ideal timing.</li>
    <li><strong>Using a tray that fits the shelf but not the crop schedule:</strong> setup fit matters, but crop timing still matters more.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Most tray mistakes come from underestimating how long peppers stay indoors and how quickly tomatoes show weakness in a tight setup.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Buy</h2>

  <p>
    For most home seed starters, choose trays that give tomatoes adequate room and peppers a little extra margin rather than trying to maximize seedling count in the smallest possible cells.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you want one tray type for both crops, lean toward the more forgiving side. If you want the best crop-by-crop fit, give peppers larger or deeper cells and let tomatoes use a slightly more moderate tray size. In many gardens, protecting seedling quality is a better investment than squeezing in more plants per tray.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Buy for the real indoor timeline, especially for peppers, not just for how many seedlings fit under the light.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The best seed starting trays for tomatoes and peppers are the ones that match how long each crop will actually need to live indoors before transplanting.
  </p>

  <p>
    Tomatoes usually tolerate a moderate tray setup if timing stays on track. Peppers usually benefit more from larger or deeper cells because they stay indoors longer and need more margin. For most gardeners, the smartest choice is a tray system that protects root room and seedling quality rather than simply maximizing plant count.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Tomatoes need a good tray. Peppers usually need a more forgiving one.
  </p>
</section>